<reference id="r_typewriter_common_formatting">
  <title>Common Formatting Types Used on a Typewriter</title>
  <shortdesc>Formatting styles are established guidelines that dictate the layout of a written document. Common types of documentation written with typewriters require different formatting styles.</shortdesc>
  <refbody>
    <section>
      <title>Common Typewriter Formatting Types</title>
      <table>
        <tgroup cols="2">
          <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1" colwidth="1.0*"/>
          <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2" colwidth="5.0*"/>
          <thead>
            <row>
              <entry>
                <p>Document</p>
              </entry>
              <entry>
                <p>Formatting Description</p>
              </entry>
            </row>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <row>
              <entry>
                <p>Letters</p>
              </entry>
              <entry>
                <p>1 inch margins, text is left justified with no first line indentation, single spaced with an extra space between paragraphs.</p>
              </entry>
            </row>
            <row>
              <entry>
                <p>Mail/Invitation Addresses</p>
              </entry>
              <entry>
                <p>Text is left justified, single spaced, and fully capitalized.</p>
              </entry>
            </row>
            <row>
              <entry>
                <p>Academic Documents (APA, MLA, CMS)</p>
              </entry>
              <entry>
                <p>1 inch margins, body text is double spaced and left justified with the first line indented. Titles are centered and references contain hanging indentation.</p>
              </entry>
            </row>
            <row>
              <entry>
                <p>Resumes and CVs</p>
              </entry>
              <entry>
                <p>1 inch margins with varied line spacing.</p>
              </entry>
            </row>
            <row>
              <entry>
                <p>Crafting/Scrapbooking</p>
              </entry>
              <entry>
                <p>Margins and spacing vary as chosen by the writer.</p>
              </entry>
            </row>
          </tbody>
        </tgroup>
      </table>
    </section>
  </refbody>
</reference>